{"text": "in gate voltage. This is characteristic of transport through an electronic bound state in the\n\nwire. A relatively trivial possibility for the origin of such a state, which is di\u000ecult to rule\n\nout experimentally121, is a conventional bound state in the middle of a short wire. The\n\nsignal from such a state in the case of a long wire would be negligible and can only arise if\n\nthere are a pair of bound states similar to the Majorana states seen in Fig. 10. However,\n\nthe same signal can arise from Andreev bound states (ABSs) at the ends of the wire that\n\nwe will discuss later137. The non-local conductance from ABSs is expected to be di\u000berent\n\nfrom those arising from Majorana modes i.e. the conductance from ABSs would not show\n\ninterference as seen in the right panel of Fig. 11. However, as mentioned, it is di\u000ecult to\n\nrule out the short wire scenario without more careful experiments such as those that have\n\nbeen proposed121.\n\nV. DISCUSSION AND CONCLUSION\n\nAfter a decade of intense search for MZMs in SM-SC heterostructures, the\n\neld is right\n\nnow at a crossroads. Tremendous e\u000borts have been invested in the past few years to improve\n\nthe quality of the various interfaces and reduce non-magnetic and magnetic disorders in\n\nthe heterostructures. This has resulted in the conversion of a soft gap characterized by a\n\nsubstantial non-zero-bias background sub-gap conductance induced by disorder scattering\n\nin the early Majorana experiments101to a near perfect hard gap in the recently realized full\n\nepitaxy InAs/Al hybrid nanowires138. Experimental progress in reducing dissipation has also\n\nresulted in substantial enhancement in the height of the zero bias conductance peak from\n\n60\n\nabout\u00180:12e2\n\nhin the\n\nrst generation Majorana devices101to zero bias conductance peak\n\nheight approaching and exceeding2e2\n\nhin the recent experiments104,112,114.", "embedding": [0.0073739165, 0.022314725, 0.00731020